abstract={When an unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) enters the environments with weak or interrupted GPS signal, the accuracy of GPS/INS integrated navigation would be decreased seriously. In this paper, a novel navigation method is proposed which can compensate the unavailable data supposed from the GPS via combining Kalman filter and Back Propagation neural network (BPNN). In order to estimate the state (i.e. velocity and position) of the UAV, Kalman filter algorithm is used to fuse GPS and INS data, which are fed into a BPNN for online training simultaneously; in the case of GPS-denied navigation, the well-trained BPNN can be employed as the replacement of GPS to ensure the precision of the navigation so that the UAV can be navigated consistently. The experimental results demonstrate that the mean bias of the UAV END position can be respectively reduced to 0.611 m, 1.397 m and 7.096 m during 450 seconds flight, which effectively solves the problem of low accuracy in GPS-denied environment.},
